thread.title: Aust dollar falls despite RBA's outlook
thread.title_full: Aust dollar falls despite RBA's outlook | Business Spectator

author: AAP
title: Aust dollar falls despite RBA's outlook
text:
The Australian dollar is lower as a boost from indications the Reserve Bank is in no hurry to cut the cash rate failed to offset overnight falls.
At 1700 AEDT on Tuesday, the currency was trading at 72.69 US cents, down from 72.73 cents on Monday.
Commonwealth Bank chief currency strategist Richard Grace said the local currency was boosted by minutes from the RBA's October board meeting.
The minutes noted the labour market had proved healthier than expected, and regulatory efforts to dampen investor activity in the property market appeared to be kicking in.
"It's had a bit of a lift from the response to the Reserve Bank's minutes," Mr Grace said.
"The minutes confirm things are looking a little rosier in the economy and this has led to an unwinding of expectations of a rate cut."
The Australian dollar had earlier hit a low of 72.42 US cents, as the greenback was boosted by well received US housing market data.
At 1700 AEDT, the Australian dollar was at 86.83 Japanese yen, up from Monday's close of 86.77 yen, and at 64.15 euro cents, up from 63.98 euro cents.
The Australian bond market was slightly weaker after the release of the RBA's minutes.
"There was a brief sell off after the Reserve Bank of Australia minutes but the market quickly moved back to pre-RBA levels," National Australia Bank fixed interest rate strategist Skye Masters said.
At 1630 AEDT on Tuesday, the December 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.355 (implying a yield of 2.645 per cent), down from 97.375 (2.625 per cent) on Monday.
The December 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.210 (1.790 per cent), down from 98.210 (1.790 per cent).
